
# Î£â€‘Gravity (Sigmaâ€‘Gravity): A Coherent Manyâ€‘Path Enhancement of Newtonian Gravity Across Solar, Galactic, and Cluster Scales

**Authors:** Leonard Speiser  
**Date:** 2025â€‘10â€‘15 (manuscript draft)

---

## Abstract

We present **Sigmaâ€‘Gravity (Î£â€‘Gravity)**, a pathâ€‘integral inspired formulation in which the gravitational influence at a field point is the **coherent sum over many geometric paths** through a baryonic mass distribution. In the **stationaryâ€‘phase limit**, this reduces to a **surfaceâ€‘density kernel** that boosts Newtonian accelerations/lensing by a locally coherent factor while **vanishing in the Solar System**.

On **galaxy scales**, a 7â€‘parameter kernel fit to **166 SPARC galaxies** achieves a **radialâ€‘acceleration relation (RAR) scatter of 0.087 dex** while satisfying Newtonian limits and conservation tests, **competitive with or better than MOND** (~0.10â€“0.13 dex).

On **cluster scales**, we construct physically realistic baryon fields (gNFW intracluster gas normalized to **f_gas(Râ‚…â‚€â‚€)=0.11**, plus BCG/ICL stars, optional clumping) and apply a **projected Î£â€‘kernel** with triaxial geometry and sourceâ€‘redshift weighting. A hierarchical calibration on **N=6 CLASHâ€‘like clusters** (Tier 1â€“2) yields a **population amplitude** Î¼_A = **4.60 Â± 0.37**, intrinsic scatter Ïƒ_A = **1.52**, and a **massâ€‘scaling of the coherence length** â„“â‚€(M) = â„“â‚€,â‹†(Râ‚…â‚€â‚€/1 Mpc)^Î³ with **Î³ = 0.087 Â± 0.10** (not yet significant, **consistent with no massâ€‘scaling**). A **blind holdâ€‘out** test predicts **A1689** with **0.12Ïƒ** residual (**pass**); **MACS1149** remains **3.8Ïƒ low**â€”consistent with missing clusterâ€‘specific sourceâ€‘redshift and/or substructure information.

Î£â€‘Gravity **passes Cassini** and **wideâ€‘binary** constraints by construction (Î£â€‘kernel â†’ 0 at small scales). We outline falsifiable predictions (stacked weak lensing, geometryâ€‘dependent strong lensing, outerâ€‘annulus galaxy tests) and provide **complete, scriptâ€‘level reproducibility**.

---

## 1. Introduction

A central tension in contemporary astrophysics is that Newtonâ€“Einstein gravity sourced by visible matter underpredicts orbital and lensing signals on galactic and cluster scales. The standard solution invokes nonâ€‘baryonic dark matter. Modified gravity programs (MOND, TeVeS, emergent gravity, f(R), etc.) alter the dynamical law or field equations. Here we instead explore a conservative hypothesis:

> Gravity sums amplitudes over many geometric paths.  
> Locally (Solar System) the stationary, shortest path dominates (Kâ†’0). At large, structured scales (galaxy disks, ICM gas) multiple families of nearâ€‘stationary paths add coherently, producing an effective boost without changing the underlying field equations.

This idea is motivated by the success of pathâ€‘integral reasoning in QED/QFT and operationalized here through two complementary kernels: (1) a galaxy kernel (pathâ€‘spectrum; stationaryâ€‘phase) used for rotation curves/RAR; and (2) a cluster kernel (projected Î£â€‘kernel) used for strong/weak lensing with full triaxial geometry. Both kernels multiply the Newtonian response by a dimensionless, geometryâ€‘gated factor that vanishes in highâ€‘acceleration, compact environments.

*What is new here* is a single, dataâ€‘driven kernel that (i) **matches the galactic RAR at 0.087 dex** without modifying GR, (ii) **projects correctly for lensing** with validated triaxial sensitivity (~20â€“30% lever arm in Einstein radius), and (iii) admits a **massâ€‘scaled coherence length** â„“_0 across halos, a discriminant absent in MOND and not predicted by NFW phenomenology. This turns Î£â€‘Gravity into a **population model** with testable hyperâ€‘parameters (A_c, â„“_{0,â‹†}, Î³).

---

## 2. Theory

### 2.1. Galaxyâ€‘scale (RAR) kernel

For circular motion in an axisymmetric disk,

g_model(R) = g_bar(R)[1 + K(R)],

with

K(R) = A_0 (g^â€ /g_bar(R))^p Â· C_coh(R;L_0,n_coh) Â· G_bulge(B/T;Î²_bulge) Â· G_shear(S;Î±_shear) Â· G_bar(Î³_bar).

Here g^â€  is an acceleration scale; (A_0,p) govern the pathâ€‘spectrum slope; (L_0,n_coh) set coherence length and damping; the gates (G_Â·) suppress coherence for bulges, shear and stellar bars. The kernel multiplies Newton by (1+K), preserving the Newtonian limit (Kâ†’0 as Râ†’0).

Bestâ€‘fit hyperparameters from the SPARC analysis (166 galaxies, 80/20 split; validation suite pass): L_0=4.993 kpc, Î²_bulge=1.759, Î±_shear=0.149, Î³_bar=1.932, A_0=0.591, p=0.757, n_coh=0.5.

Result: holdâ€‘out RAR scatter = 0.087 dex, bias âˆ’0.078 dex (after Newtonianâ€‘limit bug fix and unit hygiene). Cassiniâ€‘class bounds are satisfied with margin â‰¥10^13 by construction (hard saturation gates).

### 2.2. Clusterâ€‘scale (lensing) kernel â€” projected Î£â€‘kernel

For lensing we work directly in the image plane with surface density and convergence,

Îº_eff(R) = Î£_eff(R)/Î£_crit = Î£(R)[1+K_Î£(R)]/Î£_crit,

K_Î£(R) = A_c Â· W(R)/max_R W(R),

where W(R) is a compact, positive coherence field (a radial window or smoothed selfâ€‘convolution of Î£) that vanishes in the core, rises to a peak at lensing scales (100â€“300 kpc), and decays at large radii. The local normalization ensures A_c directly controls the amplitude without throttling by the global mass integral; this was critical to reach realistic boosts. The Einstein radius condition is âŸ¨Îº_effâŸ©(<R_E)=1.

**Triaxial projection.** We transform Ï(r) â†’ Ï(x,y,z) with ellipsoidal radius m^2 = x^2 + (y/q_p)^2 + (z/q_los)^2 and enforce mass conservation via a single global normalization, not a local 1/(q_p q_los) factor, which we showed algebraically cancels in the lineâ€‘ofâ€‘sight integral. The corrected projection recovers **~60% variation in Îº(R)** and **~20â€“30% in Î¸_E** across q_losâˆˆ[0.7,1.3].

**Massâ€‘scaled coherence.** We allow â„“_0 to **scale with halo size**: â„“_0(M) = â„“_{0,â‹†}(R_{500}/1 Mpc)^Î³, testing Î³=0 (fixed coherence) vs Î³>0 (selfâ€‘similar growth). With N=6 Tier 1â€“2 clusters including BCG and P(z_s), posteriors yield **Î³ = 0.087 Â± 0.10**â€”**consistent with no massâ€‘scaling**. Earlier analyses without these physics components suggested Î³ â‰ˆ 0.39, but better baryon modeling absorbs those effects. A definitive test requires Nâ‰ˆ18 and weakâ€‘lensing constraints.

### 2.3. Baryon models (clusters)

â€¢ **Gas**: gNFW pressure profile (Arnaud+2010 form), selfâ€‘similar scaling, normalized to **f_gas(R_500)=0.11** after a **3.2Ã— scale factor** consistent with the audit; clumping correction C(r) applied consistently (Xâ€‘ray overestimates n_e^2 â‡’ **divide n_e by âˆšC** to debias).  
â€¢ **BCG + ICL**: central stellar components included; stellar M/L consistent with strongâ€‘lensing practice.  
â€¢ **External convergence** Îº_ext ~ N(0, 0.03Â²) prior (kept small, |Îº_ext|â‰² 0.04 in our fits).  
â€¢ **Î£_crit**: Explicit Î£_crit(z_l, z_s) with proper distance ratios D_LS/D_S now fully included in all cluster inferences.

### 2.4. Safety & falsifiability

â€¢ Newtonian limit: enforced analytically; validation shows K<10^âˆ’4 at 0.1 kpc.  
â€¢ Curlâ€‘free field: conservative potential; loop curl tests pass.  
â€¢ Solar System & binaries: saturation gates keep deviations negligible (â‰«10^13 safety margin).  
â€¢ Predictions: no wideâ€‘binary anomaly; cluster lensing scales with triaxial geometry and gas fractionâ€”both testable.

